[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{With two 5-card Major suits you can transfer to either one first. A good system is to use the "weaker" transfer to show an invitational hand, the "stronger" to show a forcing to game hand.

So you bid 2\H and partner replies 2\S. What next? 

With two 5-card Major suits you can transfer to either one first. A good system is to use the "weaker" transfer to show an invitational hand, the "stronger" to show a forcing to game hand.

So you bid 2\H and partner replies 2\S. What next?

Partner now knows you have 5 \Ss, so you now bid 3\H which lets him know you have 5 of that suit also. Partner chooses the \H game. 

East plays 4\H. South leads the \H2. North wins the first trick with the \HA and returns the \H4.

Loser List: \S = 2? : \H = 1 : \D = 1 : \C = 0 :: Total = 4?

You are surely going to lose the two red Aces, so you must keep the \S losers to 1. A possible Plan is to pull the last trump and trust the \Ss to split 3-3. Good Plan?  

Stinking Plan. The chance of a 3-3 \S split is 36%, just a little over 1 in 3. A much better idea is to leave that trump out for a while longer, take your \S A K, and ruff one \S with dummy's last \H. Then what? 

Be careful, you are still in danger. You need to pull that last trump but playing \CA and a ruff at this point could result in you losing trump control. First you need to establish a \D trick, so play the \DK. 

North wins the \DA but he can't hurt you. Suppose he plays another \D. You win in dummy, ruff a \D back to your hand, and pull South's last trump. Then play a \S to North's \SQ. Your fifth \S is now established and you still have a trump to get to your hand with.

Suppose you ruffed a \S in dummy then returned to your hand by playing the \CA, then ruffing a \C.

You must then pull South's last trump, leaving you with only one trump. 

When you give up the \S to North he could play a \C, forcing you to use your last trump, and although you could take your \S winner you wouldn't have the \D trick established. Not an easy hand.}
[Play "W"]H2

